Your question is why **tableelements1** is not working with // in XPath but working without any slash, right?

You are using nested xpath. First you identified the outer element then using that you are identifying the inner element. In your case, the inner element sits right next to the outer element.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
While using xpath for inner element, we need to make an important change in xpath - &quot;.&quot;
This dot represents &quot;**From current node**&quot;. If you didn&#39;t mention &quot;.&quot;, it will apply the second locator throughout the DOM and look for match. Hence it didn&#39;t work in your case too. In short,
&quot;./&quot; ~ &quot;No Slash&quot; ~ &quot;Absolute Xpath&quot;.

Since, the second element appears next to first element, it worked without ./ itself. If you try to find some other inner element, it would not have worked. So, prefer using &quot;.//&quot; in the nested xpaths for identifying those further inner elements.

So, all these variations would work in your case:

    List&lt;WebElement&gt; tableelements1=eachtablelement1.findElements(By.xpath(&quot;div[@role=&#39;gridcell&#39;]&quot;));

xpath with ./

    List&lt;WebElement&gt; tableelements1=eachtablelement1.findElements(By.xpath(&quot;./div[@role=&#39;gridcell&#39;]&quot;));

Related articles:&lt;br/&gt;
https://sqa.stackexchange.com/a/28333/16916&lt;br/&gt;
https://github.com/seleniumhq/selenium/issues/3203

Hope I have answered your question.

